[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/11th-united-states-congress] The **11th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, consisting of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/11th-united-states-congress] It met in Washington, D.C., from March 4, 1809, to March 4, 1811, during the first two years of James Madison's presidency.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/11th-united-states-congress] The apportionment of seats in the House of Representatives was based on the 1800 United States census.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/11th-united-states-congress] Both chambers had a Democratic-Republican majority.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/11th-united-states-congress] The count below identifies party affiliations at the beginning of the first session of this congress.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/11th-united-states-congress] Changes resulting from subsequent replacements are shown below in the "Changes in membership" section.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/11th-united-states-congress] This list is arranged by chamber, then by state.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/11th-united-states-congress] Senators are listed by class, and representatives are listed by district.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/11th-united-states-congress] Senators were elected by the state legislatures every two years, with one-third beginning new six-year terms with each Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/11th-united-states-congress] Preceding the names in the list below are Senate class numbers, which indicate the cycle of their election.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/11th-united-states-congress] In this Congress, Class 1 meant their term began with this Congress, requiring re-election in 1814; Class 2 meant their term ended with this Congress, requiring re-election in 1810; and Class 3 meant their term began in the last Congress, requiring re-election in 1812.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/11th-united-states-congress] The names of representatives are preceded by their districts.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/11th-united-states-congress] The count below reflects changes from the beginning of the first session of this Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/11th-united-states-congress] There were 8 resignations, 2 deaths, 1 interim appointment, and 1 vacancy from before this Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/11th-united-states-congress] Of the voting members, there were 12 resignations, 1 death, and 1 change due to a contested election.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/11th-united-states-congress] Lists of committees and their party leaders.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1788–89 United States House of Representatives elections** were the first U.S.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] House of Representatives elections following the adoption of the Constitution of the United States.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its congressional elections, ranging from November 24, 1788, to March 5, 1789, before or after the first session of the 1st United States Congress convened on March 4, 1789.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They coincided with the election of George Washington as the first president of the United States.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the new form of government needing to be operational prior to the completion of the first national census, Article I, Section 2, Clause 3 of the U.S.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Constitution set a temporary apportionment of seats.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Among the original 13 states, 11 of them ratified the Constitution and elected 59 total representatives.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina and Rhode Island did not ratify the Constitution until after the 1st Congress began, and consequently did not elect their representatives until 1790.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Actual political parties did not yet exist, but new members of Congress were informally categorized as either "pro-Administration" (i.e., pro-Washington and pro-Hamilton) or "anti-Administration".
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first session of the first House of Representatives came to order in Federal Hall, New York City on March 4, 1789, with only thirteen members present.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The requisite quorum (thirty members out of fifty-nine) was not present until April 1, 1789.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first order of business was the election of a Speaker of the House.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] On the first ballot, Frederick Muhlenberg was elected Speaker by a majority of votes.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The business of the first session was largely devoted to legislative procedure rather than policy.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Article I, Section 2, Clause 3 of the U.S.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Constitution set a temporary congressional apportionment until the first national census was completed in 1790.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In the 18th and much of the 19th century, each state set its own date for elections.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In many years, elections were even held after the legal start of the Congress, although typically before the start of the first session.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In the elections for the 1st Congress, five states held elections in 1788, electing a total of 29 Representatives, and six held elections in 1789, electing a total of 30 Representatives.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Six seats were filled late because North Carolina and Rhode Island ratified the Constitution late.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] One pro-Administration representative resigned and the seat remained open at the end of the Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was the first special election to the United States House of Representatives.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Under the law at the time, each voter cast two votes for representative, at least one of whom had to be from a different county.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Georgia had a mixed at-large/district system for the 1st Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Representatives were elected at-large, but for three district-based seats.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Maryland had a mixed district/at-large system similar to Georgia's.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts required a majority vote, necessitating additional votes if no one won a majority.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was necessary in 4 of the districts.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] — **The Documentary History of the First Federal Elections: 1788-1790*.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New Hampshire law required a winning candidate to receive votes from a majority of voters (16.7% of votes).
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] No candidate won such a majority on the first ballot, so a second ballot was held February 2, 1789.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The election of all four representatives was contested, but the records that explained the precise grounds on which the election was contested have been lost due to the burning of Washington in the War of 1812.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] It is known to have related to questions of regularity and procedure.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] All four representatives' elections were ruled valid.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New York held elections to the 1st Congress on March 3 and 4, 1789.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They are retroactively numbered in this section.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina ratified the Constitution late and thus elected representatives to the 1st Congress in 1790.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania held elections to the 1st Congress on November 26, 1788.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] For this first election (and again in 1792 election for the 3rd Congress), Pennsylvania chose to elect all of its representatives on a single statewide general ticket, an attempt by the pro-Administration-majority legislature to prevent anti-Administration candidates from winning seats.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island ratified the Constitution late and thus elected representatives to the 1st Congress in 1790.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania] A presidential election was held in Pennsylvania on January 7, 1789, as part of the 1788–89 United States presidential election.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania] Voters chose 10 representatives, or electors to the Electoral College, who voted for President and Vice President.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania] Pennsylvania unanimously voted for nonpartisan candidate and commander-in-chief of the Continental Army, George Washington.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania] The total vote is composed of 6,718 for Federalist electors, known as the Lancaster Ticket, and 912 for Anti-Federalist electors, known as the Harrisburg Ticket, all of whom were supportive of Washington.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] An election to the United States House of Representatives was held in Pennsylvania on November 26, 1788, for the 1st Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] The United States Constitution was adopted on September 17, 1787, by the Constitutional Convention in Philadelphia, and then ratified by the States.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] Pennsylvania's legislature ratified the Constitution on December 12, 1787, by a vote of 46–23.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] On July 8, 1788, the Congress of the Confederation passed a resolution calling the first session of the 1st United States Congress for March 4, 1789, to convene at New York City and the election of senators and representatives in the meanwhile by the States.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] Pennsylvania's legislature scheduled the election for November 26, 1788, and provided for it to be held on an at-large basis.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] This was an attempt by the Federalist-dominated legislature to prevent anti-Federalist Representatives from being elected in frontier districts.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] Both parties submitted tickets with 8 candidates each.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] The large German population in Pennsylvania tended to vote for German candidates, giving the Anti-Federalist Muhlenberg and Hiester enough votes to gain seats.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-pennsylvania] The **1788 United States Senate election in Pennsylvania**, held on September 30, 1788, was the first United States Senate election held in Pennsylvania.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-pennsylvania] The Pennsylvania General Assembly, consisting of the House of Representatives and the Senate, elected Pennsylvania's first two United States Senators, William Maclay and Robert Morris.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-pennsylvania] The Anti-Federalist William Maclay was elected to the two-year staggered term of the Class I seat, while Federalist and American Founding Father Robert Morris was elected to the full six-year term of the Class III seat.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-pennsylvania] Upon the expiration of Senator Maclay's term in 1791, the State House of Representatives would not be able to elect a new United States senator due to a dispute regarding the rules and procedures of the election.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-pennsylvania] The seat was finally filled in a 1793 election.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1790–91 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between April 27, 1790, and October 11, 1791.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before or after the first session of the 2nd United States Congress convened on October 24, 1791.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was the first midterm election cycle, which took place in the middle of President George Washington's first term.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The size of the House increased to 67 seats after the new state of Vermont elected its first representatives.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] While formal political parties still did not exist, coalitions of pro-Washington (Pro-Admin.) representatives and anti-Administration representatives each gained two seats as a result of the addition of new states to the union.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Speaker Frederick Muhlenberg was succeeded by Jonathan Trumbull Jr., who became the 2nd Speaker of the House.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Either five or six incumbents did not seek re-election.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Aedanus Burke, a U.S. representative from South Carolina's 2nd congressional district, either retired or lost re-election but it is not known.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania at-large: Henry Wynkoop retired.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania at-large: Thomas Scott retired.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In this period, each state fixed its own date for congressional general elections, as early as April 27, 1790 (in New York) and as late as October 11, 1791 (in Pennsylvania).
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections to a Congress took place both in the even-numbered year before and in the odd-numbered year when the Congress convened.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In some states, the congressional delegation was not elected until after the legal start of the Congress (on the 4th day of March in the odd-numbered year).
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first session of this Congress was convened in Philadelphia on October 24, 1791.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Kentucky and Vermont became states during the 2nd Congress, adding two seats each.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The legislation admitted Vermont was passed at the end of the 1st Congress taking effect on March 4, 1791, the first day of the 2nd Congress, so that Vermont was represented from the start of the Congress, while Kentucky was unrepresented until the 2nd session.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special elections in 1790 and 1791 during the 1st United States Congress and 2nd United States Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New states and newly ratified states are not included as special elections.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections are sorted by date then district.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Connecticut elected all five of its representatives at-large on a general ticket on September 20, 1790.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were two subsequent special elections.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first was held to fill the vacancy left by Pierpont Edwards (Pro-Admin.) declining to serve and was won by Jeremiah Wadsworth (Pro-Admin.).
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The second was held September 19, 1791, to fill the vacancy left by Roger Sherman (Pro-Admin.)'s election to the Senate and was won by Amasa Learned (Pro-Admin.).
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Georgia switched to a conventional district system for the Second Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] At the time, the districts were not numbered, but are retroactively renumbered as the 1st, 2nd, and 3rd respectively here.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Kentucky was admitted during the 2nd Congress and elected its first representatives in 1792.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In Maryland, two local factions briefly emerged, the Chesapeake and Potomac (or Potowmack) "parties".
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The Potomac faction, consisting of individuals from the small counties of southern Maryland and the Eastern Shore, aimed to maintain their status by curbing the increasing influence of the city of Baltimore and the more populous counties.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] To do so, they supported the development of the federal city and a canal on the Potomac River to secure their economic future.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Conversely, the Chesapeake faction advocated for Baltimore's growth.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Their strategy involved improving the Susquehanna River to channel the lucrative wheat trade from western Maryland and Pennsylvania through Baltimore.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They also believed that political representation should reflect population growth patterns rather than be defined by the counties.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They feared that a canal on the Potomac River would undermine Baltimore's prosperity by diverting trade to competitors like Georgetown, the proposed federal city, and Alexandria.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Temporarily setting aside differences at the national level, the "Chesapeake Ticket" was formed to punish incumbents who had supported the Potomac location for the proposed federal city.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] A "Potomac Ticket" was organized and led by Governor Smallwood.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Turnout in Baltimore was around 99%, and almost every ballot was cast for the Chesapeake Ticket.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Statewide, the ticket won an overwhelming majority, securing all six seats.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This victory threatened the county-based rural oligarchy, prompting the House of Delegates to transition from a mixed system to a district-based system on December 19, 1790.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Under this new system, all of Baltimore's votes would go to just one representative, Harford County was grouped with Kent and Cecil Counties, and Anne Arundel County was grouped with Prince George's County and Annapolis.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the base of the Chesapeake "party" split between three districts, the Chesapeake faction would disappear.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts law required a majority for election.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This condition was met in four of the eight districts, the remaining four required between 2 and 9 ballots for election.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New York's districts were not numbered at the time, therefore the numbering here is retroactive.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina ratified the Constitution November 21, 1789, and elected its representatives after admission.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Due to the cession of North Carolina's trans-Appalachian territory to form the Southwest Territory, the territory of the old 5th district was lost.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina retained the same number of Representatives, and so it redistricted for the Second Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania had elected its Representatives at-large in the 1st Congress, but switched to using districts in the 2nd Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Five incumbents ran for re-election, four of whom won, while three others retired leaving three open seats.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Two districts had no incumbents residing in them, while one (the 8th district) had a single representative who declined to run for re-election and one (the 2nd district) had three incumbents, only one of whom ran for re-election.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island ratified the Constitution May 29, 1790.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] It elected its representatives after admission.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island held elections for the 2nd Congress on October 18, 1790, about six weeks after elections for the 1st Congress due to the state's late ratification of the Constitution.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont was admitted at the end of the First Congress, with the admission taking effect at the start of the Second Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont was entitled to elect two representatives.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont law at the time required a majority to win an office.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In the 1st district, no candidate won a majority, necessitating a run-off.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election] The **1790 Pennsylvania gubernatorial election** was the first gubernatorial election after the establishment of the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania as a U.S. state.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election] Thomas Mifflin, the incumbent President of the Supreme Executive Council of the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania was elected as the first Governor of Pennsylvania.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election] He defeated Federalist candidate Arthur St.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election] Clair, former Revolutionary War general and President of the Continental Congress, by a wide margin.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] Elections to the United States House of Representatives were held in Pennsylvania on October 11, 1808, for the 11th Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] Eighteen Representatives had been elected in the previous election, 15 Democratic-Republicans and 3 Federalists.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] All three Federalists and two of the Democratic-Republicans were quids, an alliance of moderate Democratic-Republicans and Federalists.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] One seat held by a Democratic-Republican had become vacant prior to this election and was filled in a special election held at the same time as this election.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] Pennsylvania was divided into 11 districts, of which four were plural districts with 11 Representatives between them, with the remaining 7 Representatives elected from single-member districts.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] Thirteen incumbents (10 Democratic-Republicans and 3 Federalists) ran for re-election, of whom 11 won re-election.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] The incumbents Jacob Richards (DR) of the 1st district, John Hiester (DR) of the 3rd district, Daniel Montgomery (DR) of the 5th district and William Hoge (DR) of the 10th district did not run for re-election.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] There was also a vacancy in the 1st district.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] One seat changed from Federalist to Democratic-Republican control.
